{"news_desk": "Editorial", "print_page": "24", "section_name": "Opinion", "subsection_name": null, "document_type": "article", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "subtype": "wide", "legacy": {"widewidth": "190", "wide": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbWide.jpg", "wideheight": "126"}, "type": "image", "width": 190, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbWide.jpg"}, {"height": 397, "subtype": "xlarge", "legacy": {"xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "397", "xlarge": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-articleLarge.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 600, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-articleLarge.jpg"}, {"height": 75, "subtype": "thumbnail", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbStandard.jpg", "thumbnailwidth": "75", "thumbnailheight": "75"}, "type": "image", "width": 75, "url": "images/2015/01/14/opinion/14wed3/14wed3-thumbStandard.jpg"}], "abstract": "Editorial welcomes announcement by New York City Comptroller Scott Stringer that city will remit total of $17 million to Robert Hill, Alvena Jennette and Darryl Austin, who were wrongly convicted of murders due to corrupt tactics of homicide detective Louis Scarcella; concedes that payout is less than men may have gotten through civil lawsuit, but that at least it is immediate and certain; calls on every state to set up some sort of monetary compensation for those who have been wrongly convicted and imprisoned.", "type_of_material": "Editorial", "word_count": "521", "lead_paragraph": "When someone has been wrongfully convicted and imprisoned, a cash payout is the most meaningful way to achieve some measure of belated justice.", "pub_date": "2015-01-14T00:00:00Z", "_id": "54b62fa638f0d82829edf1f6", "byline": {"contributor": "", "original": "By THE EDITORIAL BOARD", "person": [], "organization": "THE EDITORIAL BOARD"}, "source": "The New York Times", "snippet": "When someone has been wrongfully convicted and imprisoned, a cash payout is the most